	   <tr><td colspan=2>So in your philosophy someone who is wise has no capacity to learn? You say wisdom is how much you already know, if a wise person has no capacity to learn, does all thier knowledge come from divine help? Was it just placed in thier heads? Granted thats how alot of games give thier wisdom casters spells, but spells are not neccessarily knowledge. In my opinion, wisdom means you can learn things from watching and observing, you pikc up skils and lore form those that surround you. You watch a smith make a helm, and you can then repeat the task without having to know all the details involved or processes it takes to get the metal to the forge. Intelligence on the other hand, means you have book smarts. You can read a book, understand all the processes described, and go make something without ever having seen it done by another person. Its just two differnet ways of learning the same thing. Some peolpe possess both skills, some are intelligent without wisdom (an absent minded professor) soem are wise without intelligence (someone who can't read but can fix a car or computer or whatever). To me it makes perfect sense that whichever is higher (wis or int) is what the game uses as a check for success and skill gain. <br><br>From reading on eqtraders message boards, when it comes to smithing, whatever skill is highest between int, wis, and str is what affects skillups and success. Get one to 200 and your rates will be the same as having a different one at 200. AS far as real world sense, this may not be logical, but in the game it works to allow the warriors a chance to also have a trade skill or make thier own armor. <br><br>Just my opinion, but I think it makes perfect sense. <br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
